text:
Chernivtsi has created a shop for the production of low quality caviar
The total cost of dangerous products is over UAH 700 thousand

01 Nov 2019, 16:01

Investigators have sent to court the indictment against Chernivtsi, which created a shop for the production of low-quality black and red caviar. The total value of dangerous products distributed by the attacker on the market is over UAH 700 thousand.
Investigators from the Investigation and Business Unit of the SUNP Investigative Directorate in the Chernivtsi region found that a 46-year-old local businessman had set up a shop for the production and packaging of substandard products that was dangerous to use.
The offender arranged the production process in the garage without observing the necessary sanitary and hygienic standards. A mix of cheap raw material and caviar of different types, the attacker sold under the guise of salmon and sturgeon. He sold his counterfeit goods at two outlets in one of the Chernivtsi markets. About it reports department of communication of police of the Chernivtsi area.
During searches at the sites of manufacture and sale of counterfeit, police seized:

nearly 2.7 thousand tin and glass cans with caviar;
approximately 130 kilograms of simulated red caviar;
96 kilograms of simulated black caviar;
almost 63 kilograms of red caviar of unknown origin;
4 kilograms of expired dye red;
equipment and material for packaging products.

Samples of caviar seized by police were sent to the forensic examination for food research. According to the expert's opinion, these products do not meet the requirements of the normative documents of Ukraine for safety and quality, and their consumption can lead to food poisoning.
The investigators completed the pre-trial investigation and sent to court the indictment alleging that the offender was charged with the crime of Article 227 (Deliberate Release into the Market of Ukraine (Release on the Ukrainian Market) of Dangerous Products) of the Criminal Code of Ukraine. The sanction of this article provides for a fine of five hundred to one thousand tax-free minimum incomes of citizens with deprivation of the right to occupy certain positions or engage in certain activities for a term of up to three years.







